- Episode Length Minutes: Righ-skewed; Most episodes are under 130 minutes; but there is a presence of a smaller number of significantly longer episodes (outliers).

- Host Popularity Percentage: almost uniform; most are range from 20% to 100%

- Guest Popularity Percentage: almost uniform; range from 0 to 100%; there are some that above 100%.

- Number of Ads: This variable is strongly right-skewed. After checking the data, I found 9 records with extreme values (12, 53.37, 103.91, 103, 53.42, 103.75, 103.25, 103.25, 103.88). These might be outliers or data entry errors, and should either be replaced with the variable’s mode or removed. Most of the other values are between 0 and 3, so it may make more sense to treat this variable as categorical instead of numeric.

- Listening Time Minutes: a right-skewed distribution with a high concentration between 20 and 40 minutes, but includes episodes with significantly longer durations. To improve prediction accuracy, consider normalizing this dependent variable or employing models robust to non-normal distributions.

- Episode Number: almost uniform; data is range from 1 to 100

Podcast_Name variable has 50 unique categories. After reviewing each name carefully, I found out that the names appear to have neutral information, and many include a genre. They can be group into different genres, which is already available. And as earlier comment, genre also has a quite balanced distribution. Therefore, we can consider to drop this variable. However, to ensure we will not miss any imfortant information, i will try different models, one will be with this variable, and one without it.

2. Cleanning Data¶

(Replace outliers, missing values of each variable with its mean)

In [18]:
new_data=data.copy()
Outliers¶

- Episode_Length_minutes: Upon review, this variable appears to have two outliers.

  • The first is 325.24, which is significantly larger than the other values. I will replace it with the variable's mean.

  • The second is 0. Since Episode_Length_minutes is a float type and a podcast length of 0 minutes is not reasonable, I will also replace it with the mean.

In [19]:
ELM_mean = new_data['Episode_Length_minutes'].mean()

new_data['Episode_Length_minutes'] = new_data['Episode_Length_minutes'].apply(
    lambda x: ELM_mean if x in [0, 325.24] else x)
Null-values¶

3.2. Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)¶

In [33]:
x3=new_data.drop(columns='Listening_Time_minutes')
y3=new_data['Listening_Time_minutes']

#Perform one-hot encoding on the categorical columns

x3=pd.get_dummies(x3,drop_first=True) 

# Split data into traning and testing sets
x3_train,x3_test,y3_train,y3_test=train_test_split(x3,y3,test_size=0.2,random_state=50)

#Run XGBoost regressor model

xgb_model=XGBRegressor(objective='reg:squarederror',
                      n_estimators=100,
                       learning_rate=0.1,
                       max_depth=3,
                       randome_state=50
                      )

xgb_model.fit(x3_train,y3_train)

#Make predictions and evaluate
y3_pred=xgb_model.predict(x3_test)
mse3=mean_squared_error(y3_test,y3_pred)
rsme3=np.sqrt(mse3)
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error (RSME): {rsme3}")

    lambda x: ELM_mean_test_data if x in [0, 325.24] else x)
